      = [[Nomenclature of Territorial Units for Statistics|NUTS]] 3\n| blank3_info                     = <!-- UKG## -->\n| blank4_name                     = Ethnicity\n| blank4_info                     = 99.4% White British\n| website                         = [http://www.allerdale.gov.uk/ allerdale.gov.uk]\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n\n'''Allerdale''' is a [[non-metropolitan district]] of [[Cumbria]], England, with [[Borough status in England and Wales|borough status]]. Its council is based in [[Workington]] and the borough has a population of 93,492 according to the [[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 census]], increasing to 96,422 at the 2011 Census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=6275003&c=Allerdale&d=13&e=62&g=6411164&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1434462238094&enc=1|title=Local Authority population 2011|accessdate=16 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Borough of Allerdale was formed under the [[Local Government Act 1972]], on 1 April 1974 by the merger of the [[municipal borough]] of [[Workington]], the [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban districts]] of [[Maryport]], [[Cockermouth]] and [[Keswick, Cumbria|Keswick]]; and the [[rural district]]s of [[Cockermouth Rural District|Cockermouth]] and [[Wigton Rural District|Wigton]], all of which were within the [[administrative counties of England|administrative county]] of [[Cumberland]]. In 1995 Allerdale was granted [[Borough status in the United Kingdom|borough status]].\n\nThe name derives from the ancient region of Allerdale, represented latterly by the two [[ward (politics)|wards]] of [[Cumberland, England|Cumberland]], called Allerdale above Derwent and Allerdale below Derwent, the present borough corresponding largely to the latter with parts of the former. Much of the area during the medieval period was a [[Royal Forest]] subject to forest law.<ref>{{cite book|publisher = Alan Sutton |isbn = 0-86299-781-X |location = Wolfeboro Falls, NH |title = The royal forests of England |author = Raymond Grant |date = 1991 |id = 086299781X|ol = 1878197M }} See table, p221</ref>\n\n==Settlements==\nWorkington is the largest settlement in the borough, and is the seat of the borough council. Allerdale House in Workington is the meeting place and primary office space used by the council.<ref>{{cite web |title=Contact Us |url=https://www.allerdale.gov.uk/en/contact-us/ |website=Allerdale Borough Council |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> The building is known locally as \"Perry's Palace\" after former council leader Tony Perry, who was responsible for its construction.<ref>{{cite web |title=Former Allerdale council chief Tony Perry dies |url=https://www.timesandstar.co.uk/news/17036969.former-allerdale-council-chief-tony-perry-dies/ |website=Times & Star |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> Other settlements in the borough include: [[Abbeytown]], [[Allonby]], [[Aspatria]], [[Bolton Low Houses]], [[Bothel, Cumbria|Bothel]], [[Brigham, Cumbria|Brigham]], [[Broughton, Cumbria|Broughton]], [[Clifton, Cumbria|Clifton]], [[Cockermouth]], [[Crosby, Cumbria|Crosby]], [[Dean, Cumbria|Dean]], [[Dearham]], [[Fletchertown]], [[Flimby]], [[Ireby, Cumbria|Ireby]], [[Keswick, Cumbria|Keswick]], [[Kirkbride, Cumbria|Kirkbride]], [[Maryport]], [[Mawbray]], [[Plumbland]], [[Seaton, Cumbria|Seaton]], [[Silloth]], [[Tallentire]], [[Thursby]], [[Waverton, Cumbria|Waverton]], [[Westnewton, Cumbria|Westnewton]], and [[Wigton]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Town and Parish Council boundaries |url=https://www.allerdale.gov.uk/en/elections/town-and-parish-council-boundaries/ |website=Allerdale Borough Council |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Freedom of the Borough==\nThe following people and military units have received the [[Freedom of the City|Freedom of the Borough]] of Allerdale.\n \n{{Expand list|date=October 2019}}\n\n===Individuals===\n* [[Ben Stokes]]: 25 September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allerdale.gov.uk/en/news-and-blog/ben-stokes-to-be-made-freeman-of-allerdale/|title=Ben Stokes to be made Freeman of Allerdale|last=Irving|first=Jonathan|date=26 September 2019|website=allerdale.gov.uk|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/border/2019-09-26/ben-stokes-made-freeman-of-allerdale/|title=Stoked: Cumbrian cricket legend to be made Freeman of his home Borough|last=|first=|date=26 September 2019|website=ITV News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>\n* [[Dale Campbell-Savours|Rt Hon Lord Campbell-Savours of Allerdale]].\n* William Lowther.\n* [[Malcolm Wilson (rally driver)|Malcolm Wilson]] {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}}.\n\n==Politics==\n{{see also|Allerdale local elections}}\nElections to the borough council are held every four years with 49 [[councillors]] being elected from 23 [[Wards of the United Kingdom|wards]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Your Councillors |url=https://democracy.allerdale.gov.uk/mgMemberIndex.aspx? |website=Allerdale Borough Council |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> No party has had a majority on the council since [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] lost their majority at the [[2003 Allerdale Council election|2003 election]]. As of the [[2019 Allerdale Council election|2019 election]], the council is jointly administered by the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] and independents.<ref>{{cite web |title=England local election results 2019 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/ceeqy0e9894t/england-local-elections-2019 |website=BBC News |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref> The current leader is Cllr Marion Fitzgerald, an Independent, and the deputy leader is Mike Johnson of the Conservative Party, who replaced [[Mark Jenkinson]], when Jenkinson became the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Workington (UK Parliament constituency)|Workington]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Political structure of the council |url=https://www.allerdale.gov.uk/en/council-and-democracy/political-structure-council/ |website=Allerdale Borough Council |accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" style=\"text-align:left; padding-left:1em;\n| width=125 align=\"center\" | '''Date'''\n!style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}; width: 3px;\" |\n| width=100 align=\"center\" | '''[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]'''\n| width=20 align=\"center\" | +/-\n!style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; width: 3px;\" |\n| width=100 align=\"center\" | '''[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]'''\n| width=20 align=\"center\" | +/-\n!style=\"background-color: {{Independent/meta/color}}; width: 3px;\" |\n| width=100 align=\"center\" | '''[[Independent (politician)|Independent]]'''\n| width=20 align=\"center\" | +/-\n!style=\"background-color: {{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}; width: 3px;\" |\n| width=100 align=\"center\" | '''[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]]'''\n| width=20 align=\"center\" | +/-\n!style=\"background-color: {{United Kingdom Independence Party/meta/color}}; width: 3px;\" |\n| width=100 align=\"center\" | '''[[United Kingdom Independence Party|UKIP]]'''\n| width=20 align=\"center\" | +/-\n| width=125 align=\"center\" | '''Control'''\n|-\n\n| align=\"center\"|'''2011'''\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|28\n| align=\"right\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|12\n| align=\"right\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|15\n| align=\"right\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|1\n| align=\"right\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|0\n| align=\"right\" |\n| bgcolor=\"CCCCCC\"|[[No overall control|NOC]]\n|-\n\n| align=\"center\"|'''2013'''\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|27\n| align=\"right\" |''-1''\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|12\n| align=\"right\" |''=''\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|16\n| align=\"right\" |''+1''\n| colspan=\"2\" align=\"center\"|0\n| ali